full_text: In the previous demo, I promised to explain shared section mode fields. I start a new claim. Note the radio buttons labeled Find Policy and Create Unverified Policy. These are two different modes of this screen. The default mode is Find Policy. If I select the Create Unverified Policy button, the screen changes, allowing me to enter information about an unverified policy. If I click the Find Policy radio button, the screen returns to the default mode, Find. Let's look at how this works in Studio. We are looking at the FNUL wizard. The screen I was just looking at was the Find Policy screen. I'll double-click to open it. Recall that the main panel ref with this view includes a shared section mode field. If I click it, I have a choice between Create and Search modes. Create is the default, but if I click Search, the Search mode, which is the default in the UI, appears. Let's look at the definition of the panel ref. The definition of the panel ref is a panel set, the FNUL wizard Find Policy panel set. If I scroll down to take a look at that file, I see that there are actually two, one with the suffix, Create, and one with the suffix, Search. These suffixes define the possible modes of FNUL wizard Find Policy panel set. Logic on the panel ref determines which mode is displayed. The panel ref has a mode property. Depending on the value of page mode, a Boolean variable of the wizard, the value of this property will be either Search or Create. The value of the mode property must match the mode suffix of one of the PCF files that match the panel ref's def property. Let's look at a slightly more complicated example. If I return to the FNUL wizard, and look at its Lost Details step. I note that the step itself has a mode property. The mode property must return a text value, in this case, the claims lost type. This is determined by GOSA code that would simply be a distraction at this point. If I look at the screen property of the step, I see that it refers to FNUL wizard underscore new lost details screen. If I look at FNUL wizard underscore new lost details screen, I see that it has five modes. Four of them match the type codes for lost type, GL for general liability, PR for property, TRAV for travel insurance, and DUB-C for workers compensation. The fifth mode is default. The default screen is displayed if the mode property does not match any of the other modes, in this case, any lost type, such as auto, other than the four specified modes. Having a default mode ensures that no possible value of the mode property will go unmatched and cause a runtime error. Wizard step sets also have a mode property. However, that property is seldom used. This ends the modal PCF basics demonstration.
